data.name: rtbRenameDmon.Text
data.value:
Rename() function renames the image. You can use '*' to concatenate old name with new a new one: <exp> File name: imageExample.png
Rename(*_Horse)
New file name: imageExample_Horse.png </exp>
You can also use index of the image by adding '{#}': <exp> File names: imageExample.png imgExample.png picExample.png
Rename(*_{#})
New file names: imageExample_0.png imgExample_1.png picExample_2.png </exp>
Another keywords that you can use in your filename: '{x}' - returns image dimensions '{d}' - returns current date '{t}' - returns current time
Example of using all the keywords in one filename
<exp> Rename(EXAMPLE_{#}_{x}_{d}_{t})
Result: EXAMPLE_0_900x500_2019-01-01_12-00-00.png </exp>

data.name: rtbResizeDmon.Text
data.value:
Resize() function resizes the image.
<exp> Usage: Resize(900, 800) </exp>
Image will be 900px x 800px (W x H), but it will be stretched. To avoid this you can set filling color.
<exp> Usage: To get 900x800 image with white filling.
Resize(width, height, greyscale) Resize(900, 800, 255)
To get 900x800 image with red filling.
Resize(width, height, red, green, blue) Resize(900, 800, 255, 0, 0) </exp>
You can also add filling without changing the size, simply write '*' in place of width and height.
<exp> Resize(*, *, 255) Resize(*, *, 255, 0, 0) </exp>

data.name: rtbMarginDmon.Text
data.value:
Margin() is a function that adds margin to the image.
<exp> Usage: Margin(all) Margin(vertical, horizontal) Margin(top, right, down, left)
Example: Adds 10 pixels white border on each side. Margin(10)
Adds 20 pixels white border on the top and bottom sides and 40 pixels white border on the left and right sides. Margin(20, 40)
Adds white border on each side, each has different thickness. In this case top has 10, right 20, bottom 30 and left 40 pixels border. Margin(10, 20, 30, 40) </exp>
You can also set the color of the border.
<exp> Usage: Margin(all, grayscale) Margin(vertical, horizontal, grayscale) Margin(vertical, horizontal, red, green, blue) Margin(top, right, bottom, left, grayscale) Margin(top, right, bottom, left, red, green, blue)
Example: As you see, in some cases you have to write 'c' before the amount of color. That's because it is not clear if you want to use Margin(all, grayscale) or Margin(vertical, horizontal).
Margin(10, c0) - 10 pixels black border.
Below you can see, that 'c' is not needed, because that format is unique. Margin(10, 20, 0) - Vertical 10, horizontal 20 pixels black border.
Margin(10, 20, c0, c255, c0) - 'c' prefix needed, Margin(vertical, horizontal, red, green, blue) or Margin(top, right, bottom, left, grayscale).
Margin(10, 20, 30, 40, 0) - No prefix needed, black border.
Margin(10, 20, 30, 40, 0, 0, 255) - No prefix needed, blue border. </exp>
You can also use Margin() as cut function by using negative numbers. <exp> Example: Margin(-20) - Will cut 20 pixels on each side. Margin(-20, -50) - Will cut 20 pixels on the top and bottom sides and 50 pixels on the left and right sides. </exp>
